PUH-BrianMartell Kelvin waves in vortex reconnection are one of the most visually stunning phenomena in superfluid physics — and in PUH v15 they become a direct analog for lattice energy release during “slippage” events. In a BEC superfluid, when two quantized vortices approach and reconnect, they don’t just merge quietly. The reconnection emits a burst of helical Kelvin waves that travel along the vortex lines like ripples on a whipped rope. These waves are quantized, non-dispersive at low amplitude, and carry away the excess energy from the reconnection in the form of sound waves (phonons) when they cascade to smaller scales. In PUH terms: •  Vortex core = high-tension lattice region (similar to a PBH seed). •  Reconnection = topological slippage (weak force analog — knot re-tying). •  Kelvin waves = lattice ripples propagating along strain lines (gravitational waves or high-frequency photons from energy release).
